I want to cleanup hundreds of millions of objects from s3 bucket following set of naming convention based of age of object and storage class.
Which AWS service is best suited for this requirement?
For deleting hundreds of millions of objects in bulk based on age and storage class, the primary service you should use is Amazon S3 Lifecycle; if you need a one-time/irregular cleanup with complex filters, combine S3 Inventory + S3 Batch Operations.

When to use S3 Lifecycle
Use S3 Lifecycle rules if this is an ongoing requirement (continuous cleanup) and your filters can be expressed as:

Object age (expire objects after N days).

Storage class transitions and then expiration (e.g., move to IA/Glacier, then delete after X days).

Optional tag- or prefix-based filtering if your naming convention or tags allow it.

S3 Lifecycle is fully managed, scales to billions of objects, and automatically deletes eligible objects asynchronously without you managing jobs yourself.

When to use S3 Batch Operations
Use S3 Batch Operations if:

This is a one-off or rare cleanup of existing data at massive scale.

You have a S3 Inventory or a manifest and want to delete only a subset (e.g., specific prefixes, tags, storage classes, or objects selected by an external process).

You need to run custom logic (Lambda per object) before delete, or tag first and then let Lifecycle handle later expiration.

S3 Batch Operations can execute actions (including DeleteObject and invoking Lambda) across billions of objects using a manifest, and it manages retries and progress tracking for you.

Pragmatic pattern for your use case
Given your requirement (age + storage class + naming convention) and scale (hundreds of millions of objects):

For steady-state cleanup:

Model the retention policy via prefixes/tags + S3 Lifecycle expiration rules per prefix/tag and storage class.

For initial bulk cleanup of historical data:

Use S3 Inventory to list all objects.

Filter that offline (e.g., Athena/Glue or your own scripts) by age, storage class, and naming pattern.

Feed the resulting manifest to an S3 Batch Operations Delete job.

