Can we do it using AWS Batch?
No, AWS Batch is not suitable or recommended for this S3 object cleanup at hundreds of millions scale.

AWS Batch excels at containerized workloads (e.g., processing data with Docker jobs), but listing/deleting S3 objects directly requires either recursive ListObjectsV2 (fails at 1K objects/bucket due to pagination/API limits) or custom manifests—neither scales efficiently without the S3-native tools above.

Why AWS Batch Falls Short Here
Scale limits: Can't efficiently list billions without S3 Inventory (external to Batch); direct boto3 loops hit throttling (3,500 req/sec/account).
​

Cost/Complexity: Spinning up EC2/Fargate clusters for deletion is 10-100x costlier than Batch Operations ($0.0025/million objects) and requires custom code for retries/parallelism.
​

No native S3 integration: Batch doesn't auto-handle S3 manifests/jobs like S3 Batch Ops does.
​

Better Alternatives Already Fit
Stick with S3 Inventory + Athena + S3 Batch Operations (prior script)—it's purpose-built for this.
